<div id="review_2285367212" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2285367212" />
    <a title="Chris Dietzel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/19351209-chris-dietzel"><img alt="Chris Dietzel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501356106p2/19351209.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2285367212?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris Dietzel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris Dietzel" href="/user/show/19351209-chris-dietzel">Chris Dietzel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2285367212" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer909669602586891665">This was odd to read for a couple reasons. Instead of telling a story with a well defined plot, it reads much more like four mini biographies. Added to that is the fact that Auster uses the same Third-Person Present point of view that he would use two years later in his own biography (&apos;Winter Journal&apos;). Using the exact same voice in a work of fiction and a biography was jarring, and I couldn&apos;t help but wonder if Auster used this book as preparation for writing his own life&apos;s story or if he was o</span>
  <span id="freeText909669602586891665" style="display:none">This was odd to read for a couple reasons. Instead of telling a story with a well defined plot, it reads much more like four mini biographies. Added to that is the fact that Auster uses the same Third-Person Present point of view that he would use two years later in his own biography ('Winter Journal'). Using the exact same voice in a work of fiction and a biography was jarring, and I couldn't help but wonder if Auster used this book as preparation for writing his own life's story or if he was only comfortable writing about his own life as if it were one of his work's of fiction. As for this book, in addition to the lack of a cohesive plot, it also had a disappointing ending. I'd recommend this one only for hardcore fans of the author. </span>
  <a data-text-id="909669602586891665" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


