    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1781148219" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1781148219" />
    <a title="Chris" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/93902-chris"><img alt="Chris" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641874565p2/93902.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1781148219?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris" href="/user/show/93902-chris">Chris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1781148219" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer958023352238044069">There was a significant period of time in which I&apos;d considered Paul Auster one of the unimpeachable authors of our time - one who wrote very important things, who wrote things that came from the side of our lives that isn&apos;t always easily acknowledged. At least that much is intact... but Sunset Park is not an important piece of fiction, nor is it a particularly easily relatable work of fiction. I want to love everything Auster does, but this one... just isn&apos;t all that great.<br/><br/>I just don&apos;t see the i</span>
  <span id="freeText958023352238044069" style="display:none">There was a significant period of time in which I'd considered Paul Auster one of the unimpeachable authors of our time - one who wrote very important things, who wrote things that came from the side of our lives that isn't always easily acknowledged. At least that much is intact... but Sunset Park is not an important piece of fiction, nor is it a particularly easily relatable work of fiction. I want to love everything Auster does, but this one... just isn't all that great.<br /><br />I just don't see the importance of this novel, or of any of the characters. I think, had Auster read Almost Transparent Blue, by Ryu Murakami, he could easily have written something better - or written something altogether different.<br /><br />This is such a disjointed novel, altogether lacking in cohesion - it's a tremendous disappointment. I don't know what Auster was aiming for exactly. This misses the mark, regardless - it accomplishes very little, and leaves many questions unanswered. It's an interesting work, considering the number of very unconventional characters (for an Auster novel, that is), but it doesn't really respectfully address the direction and arc of any of these characters. Suddenly, it's just over. What a dissatisfying way to conclude the novel.<br /><br />I wish I'd set this one down at 100 pages, when I'd already sensed the pointlessness of the novel.</span>
  <a data-text-id="958023352238044069" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


