  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_187668067" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/187668067" />
    <a title="Sam Quixote" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5759543-sam-quixote"><img alt="Sam Quixote" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1529183438p2/5759543.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/187668067?book_show_action=true">Jul 23, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sam Quixote" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sam Quixote" href="/user/show/5759543-sam-quixote">Sam Quixote</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer187668067" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7037187981744523462">I wanted to like &quot;Sunset Park&quot; as Paul Auster is one of my favourite authors and has written some breathtaking books like &quot;The New York Trilogy&quot; and &quot;Moon Palace&quot;. In recent years his output has been sketchy with &quot;Travels in the Scriptorium&quot; and &quot;Man in the Dark&quot; both having moments but essentially being poor facsimiles of his early work. Last year&apos;s &quot;Invisible&quot; was a stronger effort from Auster so I hoped &quot;Sunset Park&quot; would be a better book and an original Auster masterpiece. Alas, no. <br/><br/>The boo</span>
  <span id="freeText7037187981744523462" style="display:none">I wanted to like "Sunset Park" as Paul Auster is one of my favourite authors and has written some breathtaking books like "The New York Trilogy" and "Moon Palace". In recent years his output has been sketchy with "Travels in the Scriptorium" and "Man in the Dark" both having moments but essentially being poor facsimiles of his early work. Last year's "Invisible" was a stronger effort from Auster so I hoped "Sunset Park" would be a better book and an original Auster masterpiece. Alas, no. <br /><br />The book starts out differently for Auster in the present day. Bankruptcies abound and the main character is part of the crew employed by the banks to remove the recently ousted tenants' belongings from the house. On one of his days off he meets a young girl in the park who is reading the same book as him - "The Great Gatsby" - and they fall in love. The only trouble is her age - she's 16! His relationship with her threatens to become public and so he retreats to New York, to the area Sunset Park, until she's 18 when he'll marry her. Once in Sunset Park, he meets up with other "artists" (he's a poet - remember this is an Auster novel), and they squat in this house making "art". Here the narrative stalls as the goings-on of artists become the stuff of soap operas and nothing much happens from here onwards until the ridiculous ending (which I won't spoil but is hysterical and dumb). <br /><br />It's a well written book with it's moments but far too little happens to justify it. The novel is often boring and meanders into side notes about baseball that feel like Auster simply copied down some stats and anecdotes from a baseball almanac as a way of telling the reader about the main character's love of baseball. The only recognisable part of this bit to Auster is the frequent mention of coincidences which if you've read Auster before then you'll know his fascination with this particular phenomenon. <br /><br />It's the focus on Sunset Park and it's artistes retreat that really grates though. A lot of shallow individuals wittering on about nothing in particular. It's so tedious. There is a part of the novel about PEN and it's work which is good but precious little besides this makes Sunset Park a very, very dull novel and one of Auster's few failures as a novelist. </span>
  <a data-text-id="7037187981744523462" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

